properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River at Ste. Agathe, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-29T13:00:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-28T13:08:18-05:00, 5637B65E-6AF0-EF1D-6FED-4EA9746D6EE3
Area: The Red River at Ste. Agathe, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An incoming storm system will bring strong winds and reduced visibilities in blowing snow to Resolute beginning early Wednesday morning. Visibilities are forecast to begin dropping late Tuesday night, as wind gusts are expected to be around 70 km/h combined with falling snow. Conditions will deteriorate rapidly as wind gusts increase to near 90 km/h early Wednesday morning, accompanied by heavier bands of snow. There is still some uncertainty with the timing of this storm, but current indications are that blizzard conditions could last upwards of 18 hours. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T11:29:16-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T19:30:16-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2319823397.2019
Area: Resolute
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. A warm front moving through the Northwest Territories will bring periods of freezing rain to Tuktoyaktuk and Colville Lake tonight. Freezing rain is expected to persist through the morning on Tuesday at Colville Lake. ### Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T18:13:51-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-29T02:14:51-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1663583852.2019
Area: Tuktoyaktuk - East Channel Region
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A strong low pressure system east of Churchill will continue to give snow and gusty northeast winds to Arviat today and tonight, with a further 10 cm likely. Winds are no longer expected to reach the warning threshold of 70 gusting 90 km/h though, and will remain closer to 50 gusting 70 km/h. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T06:35:22-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T14:36:22-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3150006396.2019
Area: Arviat
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Snow and blowing snow today and tonight improving on Tuesday. A low pressure system just to the northeast of Churchill continues to give snow and blowing snow to Churchill today. A slight change in its track may bring modest improvement tonight, however some snow and wind will likely continue through tonight and into Tuesday. The worst conditions will be today with visibilities near or less than 1 km. Total snowfall accumulations are expected to be in the 15 to 20 cm range by Tuesday evening. Conditions will start to improve on Tuesday as the system slowly weakens. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T09:04:11-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T17:05:11-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2778363331.2019
Area: Churchill
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain has developed in the Dawson area and will continue until near noon when the temperature rises above the freezing mark. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Utility outages may occur. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A strong low pressure system which is giving blizzard conditions to areas along the Hudson Bay coast is giving very strong north winds but lesser amounts of snow to Baker Lake this morning. Similar conditions will persist today with north winds of 70 gusting 90 km/h and around 5 cm of snow. Conditions should start to gradually improve overnight or Tuesday morning. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T06:24:47-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T14:25:47-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.4250835349.2019
Area: Baker Lake

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected. A strong low pressure system will bring damaging winds, with gusts near 100 km/h, to Paulatuk, Sachs Harbour, and Ulukhaktok later today. Blizzard conditions have developed in Paulatuk. Similar conditions will develop in Sachs Harbour and Ulukhaktok early this evening. These blizzard conditions will improve overnight tonight into Tuesday morning as the wind weakens. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T13:37:17-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T21:38:17-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2247169605.2019
Area: Sachs Harbour, Ulukhaktok, Paulatuk
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong low pressure system east of Churchill is giving blizzard conditions with northeast winds of 70 gusting 90 km/h to Chesterfield Inlet, Rankin Inlet and Whale Cove this morning. Similar conditions will persist through today, tonight, and most of Tuesday. Total snowfall accumulations could reach 30 cm in some areas, along with visibilities frequently near or less than 400 metres. Gradual improvement is expected Tuesday night when the system starts to weaken. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T06:30:50-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T14:31:50-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3310009059.2019
Area: Rankin Region including Whale Cove, Chesterfield Inlet
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong low pressure system has stalled just east of Churchill and is now starting to weaken. Visibilities have improved at Rankin Inlet so the blizzard warning has been ended there. There have been no recent reports from Chesterfield Inlet, however satellite imagery suggests the blizzard is likely still ongoing. Improvement should begin at Chesterfield Inlet some time this evening. Snow pushed farther west than originally forecast, and Baker Lake has been reporting blizzard conditions since late this morning. The blizzard will likely continue there most of the night, with gradual improvement beginning late overnight or early Tuesday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T11:33:57-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T19:34:57-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2535081553.2019
Area: Baker Lake, Chesterfield Inlet
